{"Category": "Humanities, History, STEM, Journalism, Library", "End Date": "", "Name": "Speaker Series on information and technology: Claire Wardle ", "URL": "https://events.mtholyoke.edu/MasterCalendar/MasterCalendar.aspx", "Location": "Mount Holyoke College, South Hadley, MA", "Time": "4:15-5:30pm", "Date": "Thu, Oct 19, 2017", "Organization": "Mount Holyoke College", "Emily: \ud83d\udc4d": "", "Description": "As part of a speaker series on current information and technology issues which affect society at large, LITS is hosting Claire Wardle, director of research and strategy at First Draft and, formerly, research director at the Tow Center for Digital Journalism and at the Columbia School of Journalism.  Claire is interested in all things journalism, especially social media & user-generated content.  First Draft was formed as a nonprofit coalition with nine Founding Partners in June 2015 to raise awareness and address challenges relating to trust and truth in the digital age. Their Partner Network now includes ABC, NBC, CNN, Amnesty International, Internet Archive, PBS, NYT, ProPublica, and others.\n\nAbout First Draft\n\"We provide practical and ethical guidance in how to find, verify and publish content sourced from the social web.\""},
{"Category": "Literature, Global Studies, Humanities, Arts, Theater", "End Date": "", "Name": "Author Talk: Carol Bailey", "URL": "http://www.umass.edu/events/author-talk-carol-bailey", "Location": "Umass Amherst, Amherst, MA", "Time": "5:00-7:00pm", "Date": "Thu, Oct 19, 2017", "Organization": "Umass Amherst", "Emily: \ud83d\udc4d": "", "Description": "Carol Bailey \u201907G is an associate professor at Westfield State University. Her area of teaching and research is postcolonial literatures, with specialization in Caribbean literature. Bailey is the author of A Poetics of Performance: The Oral-Scribal Aesthetic in Anglophone Caribbean Fiction (2014), in which she explores Caribbean written literature alongside calypso, reggae, and different modes of Caribbean oral storytelling, emphasizing folk and urban working-class performance cultures and a woman-centered poetics.\nBooks will be for sale.\nThe Author Talk Series is made possible through the generous support of the Friends of the Library."},
{"Category": "Humanities, History, Health", "End Date": "", "Name": "Medicine in Franklin County: 1750 to 1850", "URL": "", "Location": "Greenfield Community College, Greenfield, MA", "Time": "7:00 PM", "Date": "Thu, Oct 19, 2017", "Organization": "Greenfield Community College", "Emily: \ud83d\udc4d": "", "Description": "with Dr. Paul Berman\n\nAn overview of the types of medical care that would have been available in Franklin County between 1750 to 1850. The program will explore the theory of disease, therapeutics, alternative medicine, medical education, followed by an introduction to the physicians who practiced during these years, their backgrounds, libraries and way of life. "},
